s move to reduce corporate deposits. A reckoning for Spacs: will regulators=
 deflate the boom? Rental Companies Buy Up Used Cars as  Chip Crisis Get Wo=
rse. Fund Companies Push Diversity in Bond Trading. Michael Jackson=E2=80=
=99s Estate Is Winner in Tax Judge=E2=80=99s Ruling. IMDb TV is producing =
=E2=80=9C=E2=80=98The Fed,=E2=80=99=C2=A0which follows the personal and car=
eer drama surrounding a group of young finance hopefuls as they begin an el=
ite fellowship with the Federal Reserve, the nation=E2=80=99s most powerful=
 financial institution. These young financial geniuses are destined for gre=
atness =E2=80=94 provided they don=E2=80=99t screw it all up with secrets, =
lies, sex, and politics.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0To Mars Wrigley, Getting High on  =
=E2=80=98Medicated=E2=80=99 Skittles Is No Joke.=C2=A0If you'd like to get=
=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, pleas=
e=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and othe=
r great Bloomberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] I think there are cases of c=
ompanies unilaterally shipping orders a week before they were supposed to a=
nd then saying =E2=80=9Coops, well, now you have it, no big deal right,=E2=
=80=9D when the customers call to complain, but it=E2=80=99s probably easie=
r to get the customers=E2=80=99 permission instead.[2]=C2=A0=E2=80=9CConced=
ed=E2=80=9D is maybe a strong word; the SEC says in a footnote that it =E2=
=80=9Cdoes not make any findings that revenue from these sales was not reco=
rded in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles.=E2=80=9D[=
3] You can find the actual formula in the prospectus, under =E2=80=9CDaily =
ETN Performance.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0[4] In theory you can sort of replicate the =
VIX with options on the S&P 500 index, but it=E2=80=99s a lot harder than r=
eplicating, say, the S&P 500 by buying all the stocks in the index.[5] Actu=
ally the futures expire, so you need to roll them, and the underlying index=
 incorporates a roll. Still, you don=E2=80=99t need to adjust your hedge *m=
uch*.[6] These numbers are made up. The XIV notes are based on an index cal=
culated from=C2=A0a couple of short-term VIX futures; the Bloomberg ticker =
for that index is SPVXSPID. The levels of that index don=E2=80=99t correspo=
nd intuitively=C2=A0to actual VIX levels, but the basic sense here is rough=
ly right. On Feb. 5, 2018, that index opened a bit above its previous close=
 of 49.43; it traded up to about 66 as of 4 p.m. Then it spiked up to 87.5 =
by 4:15 p.m. Meanwhile VIX spiked from roughly 17 to 33 that day.[7] The ma=
th here is that if you=E2=80=99re short $2 billion of futures at 30 (the cl=
osing price the previous day),=C2=A0and then you buy them back at=C2=A0an a=
verage price of 52, you pay an extra 73% =E2=80=94=C2=A0you sold them for $=
2 billion and bought them back for $3.46 billion.[8] At the time, I  publis=
hed a wild guess that Credit Suisse made $100 million, based on the hedging=
 slippage in a similar exchange-traded fund. According to the Second Circui=
t opinion we discuss below, the=C2=A0people suing Credit Suisse estimate th=
at the real number is =E2=80=9Cbetween $475 and $542 million.=E2=80=9D That=
=E2=80=99s a wide range, and you=E2=80=99d have to see their actual hedging=
 performance, but the point is that it=E2=80=99s almost certainly a large n=
umber. At the time, Credit Suisse coyly said =E2=80=9Cthat it has experienc=
ed no trading losses from VelocityShares=C2=A0Daily Inverse VIX Short Term =
ETNs (=E2=80=98XIV=E2=80=99),=E2=80=9D because I guess people were confused=
 and thought it might have lost money hedging, but it did not mention how m=
uch money it actually *made*.=C2=A0[9] There were  rumors to that effect at=
 the time, and if you read the Second Circuit opinion you will see some hyp=
othetical discussion of the theory. For instance on page 24, the court says=
 that, in Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s view, =E2=80=9Cthe complaint alleges that=
 Credit Suisse had fully hedged itself by acquiring alternative hedging ins=
truments after the July 2016 Announcement. Thus, Credit Suisse would have h=
ad no need to trade VIX futures contracts at all on February 5, 2018 and th=
erefore could not have manipulated the market for XIV Notes by doing so.=E2=
=80=9D Credit Suisse is not quite saying =E2=80=9Cwe laid off all the risk,=
=E2=80=9D but it is saying something like =E2=80=9Cif we had laid off all t=
he risk that would be fine.=E2=80=9D[10] Your Hometown Deli is the name of =
the deli; Hometown International Inc. is the name of the public company tha=
t owns it. It is conventional in the press to refer to it as a $100 million=
 deli, which is its basic market capitalization, but I have insisted that i=
t is  actually a $2 billion deli, based on its fully diluted market capital=
ization. (All of these numbers are somewhat kidding, as the stock barely tr=
ades, but if you=E2=80=99re going to pick a number the $2 billion one feels=
 right-ish.) Anyway the New Yorker is with me: =E2=80=9CHometown is current=
ly valued at two billion dollars.=E2=80=9D
