10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note: </strong><em>Despite=
 yesterday=E2=80=99s programming note, here Money Stuff is today. But it wi=
ll be off tomorrow, back on Thursday. Sorry for the confusion.</em></p><h2 =
style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, He=
lvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30=
px; margin-bottom: 0;">Short-termism</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One t=
heory is that the price of a share of stock reflects the present value of i=
ts future cash flows in=C2=A0perpetuity. People buy stock today not because=
 they expect high profits tomorrow, but because they expect high profits ov=
er the long run. Investment decisions that cost money today, but that will =
bring in much more money in five years, increase the net present value of t=
he stock, so the shareholders should support them.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Another theory is that public markets are myopically focused =
on the short term. Investors care only about this quarter=E2=80=99s earning=
s; they buy stocks whose earnings go up each quarter and sell stocks whose =
earnings go down. A decision that reduces earnings today, in exchange for h=
igher earnings in the future, is bad, and shareholders will punish a compan=
y that makes those decisions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These theorie=
s obviously conflict, and I am mostly inclined to believe the first one.=C2=
=A0The number of zero-revenue electric-vehicle companies that go public at =
multibillion-dollar valuations seems to me like proof that public stock mar=
kets can look past this quarter and consider future profits. Still, for mos=
t regular companies, this quarter=E2=80=99s earnings probably are the best =
evidence of what future earnings will look like, so investors do tend to ca=
re. And public-company executives =E2=80=94=C2=A0not all of them, but some =
of them =E2=80=94 do sometimes get locked into a myopic obsession with each=
 quarter=E2=80=99s numbers.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Often this deba=
te is sort of vague and abstract, and it=E2=80=99s hard to tell if a compan=
y is really trading off long-term profitability against short-term earnings=
. But=C2=A0here=E2=80=99s a sad little <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/23739257.287527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZX=
NzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMS03OA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa1c51635" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">U.S. Securities and Excha=
nge Commission enforcement action</a> against Under Armour Inc. for =E2=80=
=9Cpulling forward=E2=80=9D revenue. Under Armour had a long history of gro=
wing revenue at a 20% year-over-year rate every quarter. It was proud of th=
is history, it mentioned it in earnings releases and on earnings calls, and=
 investors and analysts came to expect consistent 20% growth rates.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Having consistent 20% growth rates is good! If you=
 keep growing revenue at 20% a year, your future revenue will be really hig=
h! If investors can project 20% revenue growth rates forever =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0not forever, obviously, but for a long time =E2=80=94=C2=A0then they wil=
l put a very high value on your stream of future cash flows, and so they wi=
ll pay a lot for your stock. Having a 20% growth rate every quarter is good=
 evidence that your future growth rates will be high. Having your growth ra=
te decline below 20% is good evidence that your future growth rates will be=
 lower. Not proof, in either case, but evidence.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">In the third quarter of 2015, Under Armour realized its sales were no=
t going to be what analysts expected. So it said, well, we already have som=
e sales planned for the fourth quarter, why not just move those into the th=
ird quarter? So it called up customers and asked them to take their orders =
early, so <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23739257=
.287527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjEvMzMtMTA5NDA=
ucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9ea28b99" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">they could be booked into the third quarte=
r</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To close the emerging re=
venue gap, Under Armour=E2=80=99s senior management directed the FP&amp;A [=
Financial Planning &amp; Analysis] group and senior sales personnel, among =
other things, to identify existing orders that customers had requested be s=
hipped in the next quarter that could instead be shipped in the current qua=
rter. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ultimately, Under Armour pu=
lled forward approximately $45 million in orders from the fourth quarter of=
 2015 into the third quarter of 2015. On October 22, 2015, Under Armour ann=
ounced revenue of $1.204 billion for the third quarter of 2015, beating ana=
lyst consensus by $29 million. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Un=
der Armour did not disclose that it used pull forwards, despite the fact th=
at nearly 4% of its total revenue for the third quarter of 2015 (approximat=
ely $45 million) resulted from the practice. Without the pull forwards from=
 the fourth quarter of 2015, Under Armour=E2=80=99s growth rate for the thi=
rd quarter of 2015 would have been below analysts=E2=80=99 revenue estimate=
s and the lowest quarterly growth rate in more than two years.</p></blockqu=
ote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this created a problem in the fourth q=
uarter: Under Armour moved $45 million of fourth-quarter revenue into the t=
hird quarter, which meant that it started $45 million behind in the fourth =
quarter. So it pulled $99 million of revenue forward in the fourth quarter.=
 This created a problem in the first quarter of 2016:</p><blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By February 2016, the gap between internal forecasts=
 and external revenue guidance was so significant that Under Armour conside=
red revising its public revenue guidance for the quarter =E2=80=93 somethin=
g the company had never done before. An Under Armour senior executive ackno=
wledged the challenges caused by the 2015 pull forwards by stating in an em=
ail: =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s see how of [sic] this goes and if we can get en=
ough pull-forwards or extra business to close the Q1 gap. The issue is that=
 we pulled forward a lot in Q4 and there is not as much room in Q2 but we w=
ill see.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Etc. T=
his kept going=C2=A0until the fourth quarter of 2016, when Under Armour pul=
led forward $172 million of revenue but then decided it was all getting to =
be too much:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because Under Armo=
ur could not meet analysts=E2=80=99 revenue estimates even with the $170 mi=
llion in pull forward sales, a senior Under Armour executive made the decis=
ion to limit additional pull forwards from 2017 into 2016. Notes from a Dec=
ember 15, 2016 meeting of the company=E2=80=99s top executives reflect that=
, while discussing his decision, the senior executive stated that the compa=
ny had =E2=80=9Cbeen living in this bubble for a while,=E2=80=9D that pulli=
ng forward revenue in each quarter was not healthy, and that the company wa=
s =E2=80=9Cnot going to compromise 2017 . . . we=E2=80=99re not going to ta=
ke from next year.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A =
couple of points. First, this problem really does get worse over time:</p><=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The impact of these shifting sales =
was especially pronounced for Under Armour because prior reported revenue, =
particularly in the third and fourth quarters of 2015, included a significa=
nt amount of pull forwards. Therefore, to meet analysts=E2=80=99 revenue es=
timates for 2016,=C2=A0Under Armour had to replace the sales it had previou=
sly taken from 2016 through additional customer demand and new products, bu=
t also demonstrate the same percentage revenue growth when compared to the =
2015 revenue totals (which in turn had been enhanced with pull forwards). I=
n internal emails, Under Armour acknowledged this =E2=80=9Cdouble impact on=
 the growth rate=E2=80=9D resulting from pull forwards because they =E2=80=
=9Ctake the base up=E2=80=9D in the earlier year and down in the later year=
.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, you can=E2=80=99t ju=
st unilaterally pull forward revenue; you have to call up customers and ask=
 them to take products early.[1] This is awkward, both in the sense that th=
e customers will be annoyed, but also in the sense that you will create an =
unfortunate record for the SEC to look at later:</p><blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">For example, in September 2016, Under Armour requested ad=
ditional pull forwards from a key customer, after already having asked to m=
ove more than $30 million in sales from the fourth quarter of 2016 to the t=
hird quarter of 2016. The customer responded by saying: =E2=80=9CWe just br=
ought a bunch of your goods in early to help out your quarter. . . Now you =
want more. . . More..More..more..30% [price discount] please.=E2=80=9D Unde=
r Armour ultimately agreed to a 25% price discount and an extra 30 days to =
pay to secure an additional $6.7 million of pull forwards.</p></blockquote>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Under Armour was willing to take 75 cents this=
 quarter instead of 100 cents the next quarter, because it needed to beat a=
nalyst estimates this quarter. That is not economically rational, and share=
holders discounting all future cash flows would not want their company to p=
ay up so much to accelerate cash flows by a month. Nevertheless it happened=
. Under Armour strictly preferred beating quarterly analyst expectations to=
 maximizing the net present value of its cash flows.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Third, the SEC charged Under Armour with securities fraud, and Un=
der Armour settled by paying $9 million without admitting or denying the ch=
arges. But the SEC conceded that Under Armour=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>accounting=
=C2=A0</em>was correct.[2] All the pulled-forward sales really happened, an=
d were booked into the quarters when they happened; Under Armour=E2=80=99s =
income statements accurately reflected its revenue each quarter.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem is that Under Armour created a misleading=
 impression of=C2=A0<em>how=C2=A0</em>it got those earnings: In its earning=
s releases and calls and securities filings, Under Armour said the usual th=
ings about how it kept growing, and how the growth=C2=A0was due to things l=
ike =E2=80=9Cgrowing interest in performance products, the strength of the =
Under Armour brand in the marketplace, and increased sales and new offering=
s in footwear and apparel.=E2=80=9D Instead of saying =E2=80=9Cwell we keep=
 growing because we pester customers to take next quarter=E2=80=99s deliver=
ies this quarter, which is unsustainable.=E2=80=9D If it had said that, inv=
estors would have understood the real story; they would not have interprete=
d consistent quarterly revenue growth as evidence of future revenue growth.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fourth, this sort of lite fraud =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0not accounting fraud, just fraud in the explanation if you will=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0is=C2=A0in the abstract hard to prove. Calling a customer a=
nd saying =E2=80=9Chey you should buy more of our products and sooner rathe=
r than later=E2=80=9D could be gimmickry to meet quarterly numbers, but it =
could also be good aggressive sales tactics.=C2=A0The way you know it=E2=80=
=99s gimmickry is mostly that Under Armour executives kept emailing each ot=
her to say it was:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An Under Arm=
our senior executive acknowledged that the desire to ship the product early=
 was being driven by pressure to meet analysts=E2=80=99 revenue estimates, =
saying that the customer =E2=80=9Cisn=E2=80=99t setting [Under Armour produ=
ct in its stores] until February, so whether we thought it was $20 or $53 [=
million] or whatever, really [the customer] doesn=E2=80=99t want any of tha=
t product in December but we are shipping it and they are absolutely taking=
 it from us as a favor. If we were a privately held company, we would not s=
hip that product to them in December.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Internally, Under Armour knew that the company relied heavily=
 on pull forwards to meet analysts=E2=80=99 revenue estimates, and the comp=
any=E2=80=99s senior management implicitly admitted the unsustainability of=
 this practice by describing pull forward revenue as =E2=80=9Cbad,=E2=80=9D=
