Suisse Group AG used to have a product called XIV, which was pronounced not=
 =E2=80=9Cfourteen=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9CVelocityShares Daily Invers=
e VIX Short-Term ETN.=E2=80=9D XIV was an exchange-traded note linked to th=
e inverse of the VIX, the CBOE Volatility Index, which is a measure of vola=
tility in the stock market. If you wanted to bet that volatility would go=
=C2=A0<em>down</em>, you could buy XIV, which went up in value when the VIX=
 went down and vice versa. XIV was an exchange-traded note, meaning that yo=
u could buy it on the stock exchange (like an exchange-traded fund) but ult=
imately it was an obligation of Credit Suisse, which would calculate the va=
lue of the note and pay you that value. If volatility went down, Credit Sui=
sse owed you more money; if it went up, Credit Suisse owed you less.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine structuring a product like that=
