 the VIX is at 15, $10 more for every point below that, and $10 less for ev=
ery point above that; at a VIX of 25 the notes go to zero.=E2=80=9D (Or wha=
tever you think the numbers should be.) But that is not how XIV was structu=
red. Instead, the way XIV worked was that it was indexed to a couple of nea=
r-term VIX=C2=A0<em>futures=C2=A0</em>contracts. There is a traded market f=
or futures contracts, bets on the future price of the VIX; the way XIV work=
ed is that, each=C2=A0day, you=E2=80=99d measure how much those futures con=
tracts were up (or down) over the day before, and the value of XIV would de=
cline (or increase) by that percentage amount.[3]=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">There=E2=80=99s a reason for this, which is that Credit Suisse=
 had to hedge its XIV exposure, and the way to hedge an inverse VIX exposur=
