margin: 16px 0;">The claim is not just that Credit Suisse bought a bunch of=
 futures at the close on Feb. 5, 2018, pushing around the market; it=E2=80=
=99s that Credit Suisse=C2=A0<em>sold too many XIV notes precisely so that =
its futures trading would push around the market.=C2=A0</em>There had been =
three volatility spikes before Feb. 5, 2018, and each time Credit Suisse=E2=
=80=99s hedging seemed to affect the market for VIX futures. =E2=80=9CPursu=
ant to Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s internal risk protocols, all three of these =
liquidity incidents were promptly reported to Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s Capit=
al Allocation and Risk Management Committee (CARMC),=E2=80=9D and afterward=
s =E2=80=9CCredit Suisse=C2=A0sought alternative ways to hedge its own expo=
sure to XIV Notes,=E2=80=9D besides trading futures, though it=E2=80=99s un=
clear if it found them.=C2=A0But then it also started selling a bunch more =
XIV notes.=C2=A0</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The complaint =
plausibly alleges that Credit Suisse knowingly or recklessly exacerbated th=
e liquidity squeeze it had already observed in the VIX futures market by in=
creasing the number of XIV Notes outstanding through its offerings of June =
30, 2017 and January 29, 2018. When Credit Suisse offered 16,275,000 XIV No=
tes on the latter date, it knew that the scale of its hedging strategy woul=
d have to increase to account for its additional sales even though the liqu=
idity in the VIX futures market would remain roughly the same. From these f=
acts, a reasonable juror could conclude that Credit Suisse and the Individu=
al Defendants sold millions of these notes either knowing or recklessly dis=
regarding a substantial risk that, when the next volatility event occurred,=
 Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s hedging trades would have an even greater negative=
 impact on the value of XIV Notes than they had before. Moreover, the compl=
aint specifically alleges that the Individual Defendants were aware of this=
 risk, as Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s expansion of XIV Notes breached internal =
risk limits and thus required approval by CARMC. Accepting these allegation=
s as true, the complaint invites a reasonable inference that Credit Suisse =
increased the volume of XIV Notes for a manipulative purpose=E2=80=94specif=
ically, to ensure that Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s hedging trades would destroy=
 the value of XIV Notes during the next volatility spike so that Credit Sui=
sse could profit by declaring an Acceleration Event.</p></blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly, Credit Suisse defends itself by saying, l=
ook, we disclosed in the prospectus that we would hedge by trading futures,=
