are true, it seems like Credit Suisse hedged in a fairly textbook way, and =
I can=E2=80=99t really imagine that there are emails at Credit Suisse sayin=
g =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s sell more XIV notes so that, when volatility spike=
s, our hedging can destroy the value of the notes.=E2=80=9D It seems unlike=
ly that Credit Suisse=C2=A0<em>wanted=C2=A0</em>this result; it was clearly=
 embarrassed that its XIV product blew up, and also embarrassed that it mad=
e money on the blowup. It strikes me as very far-fetched to think that Cred=
it Suisse=C2=A0<em>plotted to blow up XIV</em>.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">But it is unlikely that I=E2=80=99ll be on the jury. To a normal=
 person, the schematic argument =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9Cyou pushed down the pric=
e of XIV, we lost everything, you made money=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0is pre=
tty compelling! Even without bad chats proving intent, the schematic argume=
nt almost <em>sounds=C2=A0</em>like it proves intent. And now the investors=
 get to make it.</p>
